obo:ECO_0001225  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_4576  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: - DIP2A is involved in acetylated coenzyme A (Ac-CoA) synthesis and is primarily expressed in the brain regions with abundant pyramidal neurons.\n\n- DIP2A is localized to dendritic spines in excitatory neurons (Fig.1) - shown with Western Blot of synaptosomes and fluorescence microscopy of cultured neurons\n\n- deletion of Dip2a in mice induces defects in spine morphogenesis along with thin\npostsynaptic density (PSD), and reduced synaptic transmission of pyramidal neurons (Fig. 2) - as shown with fluorescence microscopy, whole-cell patch clamp, Western Blot and TEM\n\n- DIP2A interacts with cortactin, an activity-dependent spine remodelling protein, and modulates its acetylation (Fig. 3) - shown by Western Blot of mural brain lysates and fluorescence microscopy\n\n- Acetylation cortactin is critical for DIP2A-regulated synaptic transmission. Acetylation mimetic cortactin rescues synaptic defects. (Fig. 6) - shown with whole-cell patch clamp of 8KQ infected Dip2a KO neurons at DIV10. Experimental description: Dip2a KO mice were generated using CRISPR/Cas9 technology and backcrossed with C57BL/6 over 9 generations. Heterozygous Dip2a KO mice were crossed for producing offspring. Littermate mice of WT and KO genotypes were allocated randomly for experiments. Primary cortical neurons were isolated from P0 pups." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2023-01-30" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4576" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

